\subsection{How hashlines work}{

\code{\link[=btw_tool_files_read]{btw_tool_files_read()}} annotates each line of the file
with a short content hash in the format \code{line_number:hash|content}, e.g.
\code{2:d6a|library(btw)}. The 3-character hash is derived from
\code{\link[rlang:hash]{rlang::hash()}} over the line content (trimmed of leading/trailing
whitespace and truncated to 80 characters).

When the model submits an edit, it references specific lines by their
hashline, e.g. \code{"2:d6a"}, which ensures that the edit is applied precisely to
the intended line. If the file has changed since the last read, the hashline
references will not match the current file state, and the edit will be
rejected with a hash mismatch error, prompting the model to re-read the file.
}

\subsection{Edit actions}{

\code{btw_tool_files_edit()} supports three types of edit actions, each using
hashline references for validation:
\itemize{
\item \code{"replace"}: Replace a single line. The model provides a \code{line} with a
single hashline reference, e.g. \code{"2:d6a"}, and \code{content} to replace the
line. The model can also remove the line by providing empty \code{content}.
\item \code{"insert_after"}: Insert new lines after a reference line. The model
provides a \code{line} with a hashline reference and \code{content} with the lines to
insert after it. The model can also insert at the start of the file using
\code{line = "0:000"}.
\item \code{"replace_range"}: Replace a range of consecutive lines. The model provides
a \code{line} with two hashline references indicating the start and end of the
range, e.g. \code{"10:a3f,15:b2c"}, and \code{content} with the replacement lines.
}

Multiple edits in a single call are allowed and are applied together: all
succeed or all fail. Edits must not have overlapping line ranges.
